President Obama has signed an emergency declaration for North Dakota due to the flooding that began on April 22, 2013. This declaration allows the Department of Homeland Security, specifically the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to alleviate the hardship and suffering caused by the emergency. FEMA is authorized to mobilize and provide necessary equipment and resources to mitigate the impacts of the emergency. Emergency protective measures will be provided at 75 percent federal funding. Gary R. Stanley has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for federal recovery operations in the affected area.